You are here: Home / Faculty : Suzanne M. StaufferFaculty : Suzanne M. Stauffer





Suzanne M. Stauffer
Associate Professor
Russell B. Long Professor
Louisiana State University
School of Library and Information Science
277 Coates Hall
Baton Rouge, LA 70803
Phone: 225-578-1461
Fax: 225-578-4581
stauffer@lsu.edu




PhD, Library and Information Science, University of California, Los Angeles
MLS, Library Science, Brigham Young University, Provo, Utah
BS,  Psychology, Weber State University, Ogden, Utah
 
My involvement with the public library began with my first job at 15 as a page in public library and later in the high school library and my undergraduate college library. Professional experience includes two years as Adult Services/General Reference Librarian in Long Beach, New York, eight years as Technical Services Librarian at Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion in New York City, and two years as a children’s librarian for the County of Los Angeles. While a doctoral student, I worked as a part-time/temporary cataloger for Cotsen Children’s Collection, a reference librarian and cataloger for Occidental College, and a cataloger for the Frank D. Lanterman Regional Center. I also taught reference & cataloging for San Jose State University and cataloging for UCLA as adjunct faculty.
 
I a member of the American Library Association, and have served on the Research and Development Committee of the Association for Library Services to Children, as Secretary-Treasurer of the Library History Round Table and member and chair of the Justin Winsor Essay Prize Committee. I was a member and later chair of the Association for Library and Information Science Education Teaching Excellence Award Committee and a member of the Research Grants Awards Committee. I am also a member of the American Culture Society and of SHARP : Society for the History of Authorship, Reading and Publishing. I am past book reviews editor for Cataloging & Classification Quarterly.
 
I am currently a senator in the Faculty Senate, a member of the SLIS Awards, Scholarship and Recruitment Committee, and a member of the CHSE Awards Committee and the CHSE Recruitment Committee. I am a past member of the LSU Faculty Senate International Education Committee.
 
 
Courses Taught 
LIS 7101 Media and Services for Children
LIS 7104 Non-Fiction for Children and Teens
LIS 7105 Graphic Novels in Libraries
LIS 7400 School Media Centers
LIS 7700 History of Books and Libraries
LIS 7800 The Art and Practice of Library Storytelling
 
Areas of Interest
The American public library and print culture
History of the American public library as a social and cultural institution
History of children’s services in public libraries
Children’s print culture
History of the professionalization of librarianship and education for librarianship
Gender issues in public librarianship
 
Selected Publications 
2014 Stauffer, Suzanne M. “The Intelligent, Thoughtful Personality : Librarianship as a Process of Identity Formation.” Library & Information History, 30 : 4 (November 2014), 254–272.

2014 Stauffer, Suzanne M. “The Dangers of Unlimited Access: Fiction, the Internet and the Social Construction of Childhood.” Library & Information Science Research, 36 : 3-4 (October 2014), 154-162.

 
Selected Presentations
2014 History of Librarianship, International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions Annual Conference, Satellite Conference, August 25-26, 2014, Lyon, France. Presented paper “Let Us Forget this Cherishing of Women in Library Work : Women in the American Library War Service, 1918-1920.”
 
2014 Library History Round Table Research Forum, American Library Association Annual Conference, June 26-July 1, 2014, Las Vegas, NV. Presented paper “Supplanting the Saloon Evil and Other Loafing Habits: Utah’s Library-Gymnasium Movement, 1907-1912.”
 
Selected Grants/Funded Projects 
2011-  Grant award number RE-01-09-0013 Institute of Museum and Library Services $763,901. Project title “Project Recovery : Educating the Next Generation of Librarians for South Louisiana.” Replaced Dr. Robert Ward as Co-Investigator, Public Libraries. Dr. Alma Dawson, Principal Investigator and Project Director.  7/1/2009-6/30/2012.
